<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-712-844  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 712 844.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  August 6 1990 v9 n16 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Officials convicted of conspiracy to defraud. (Automated DataManagement Inc., four senior officials convicted by US DistrictCourt of tax evasion, conspiracy to defraud the government)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Automated Data Management Inc. (cases).andO;Topic:     FraudGovernment ContractsCourt CasesContracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Officials Convicted of Conspiracy to DefraudandM;Automated Data Management Inc. and four of its senior officials wereconvicted last month by a U.S.andP;  District Court jury in Washington ofconspiracy to defraud the government, tax evasion and other charges.andM;The charges against the Washington company stemmed from a 1985 Army contractunder which ADM supplied microcomputers made by Wang Laboratories Inc.andM;In a separate action, U.S.andP;  District Judge Lowell Reed Jr.andP;  in Philadelophiasentenced two officials of General Electric Co. to prison terms and fined GE$10 million.andP;  The sentences and fine came as a result of charges that thecompany defrauded the Army while providing the service with battlefieldcomputers.andM;The ADM contract, known as Microcomputer System-8A, was worth about $90million to the company before it expired earlier this year, an Armyspokeswoman said.andM;The verdict against the minority-owned contractor came after a two-monthtrial.andP;  ADM officials were charged with setting up bogus companies in severalforeign countries and using the companies to generate about $800,000 worth offictitious invoices, later billed to the Army.andM;The company also was convicted of producing about $500,000 of fictitiousinvoices related to software development work that never was performed.andM;The guilty verdicts were returned against Michelle Ashton, ADM's presidentfDavid Dale, executive vice president; Terrence Sweeney, vice president; andMartin Segal, chief financial officer.andM;Charges ranged from tax evasion to making false statements to the government.andO;U.S.andP;  Attorney Jay B. Stephens said the convictions &quot;demonstrate thatindividuals who evade their responsibility to deal honestly and fairly withthe [government] will be held accountable.&quot;andM;Ashton and Dale face a maximum of 33 years in prison and fines of up to $1million, according to Judy Smith, a spokeswoman in the U.S.andP;  attorney'soffice.andP;  Sweeney could receive a maximum of 18 years in prison and a $1million fine, she said, and Segal faces 13 years and a $750,000 fine.andO;Sentencing is set for Oct. 22.andM;Sentencing of GE and its officials followed a March conviction in which afederal court jury in Philadelphia found that one official fraudulentlyovercharged the Army $8 million and another covered up the fraud.andM;The verdict steemed from a 1979 contract with the Army to provide hardwarefor the Decentratized Automated Service-3 (DAS-3) program, a battlefieldcomputer system.andP;  The executives were charged with negotiating pricereductions with about 30 DAS-3 subcontractors and submitting incorrectdocuments to the Army afterward.andM;As a result of the conviction, Gerald A. Leo, an official with GE'sManagement and Technical Services Co. (MATSCO), was sentenced to 10 months inprison and fined $15,000.andP;  James Badolato, also a MATSCO official, received afive-month prison term and a fine of $10,000.andM;U.S.andP;  Attorney David Howard said GE's $10 million fine was negotiated betweencompany and government lawyers as part of an agreement that also calls forthe company to waive its right to appeal.andP;  GE also will pay the governmentanother $8.3 million to compensate for the fraud and $11.7 million as aresult of what Howard called &quot;other civil disputes.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>